The Limit of Panic
Copenhagen—We are often told how the world we know will face the end of times, typically in terms of ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Roman Club published the influential book "The Limits to Growth" nearly forty years ago, its basic idea has been with us all the time.
Time is not forgiving.
The Limits to Growth in 1972 warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was at hand.
But what we saw after that was a financial panic, but no actual shortages or collapse in production.
On the contrary, human resources created by human genius are more than sufficient to meet human consumption.
But the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds: we continue a trend, getting stuck on misleading solutions to minor issues, while ignoring major problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, the optimism about technology faded, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society plunged into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book Silent Spring ignited a wave of fear about pollution and sparked the modern environmental movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 bestseller The Population Bomb made the point.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were pessimistic.
The intention of "The Limits to Growth" is to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people consume too many things.
Even if our genius gains us some time, we will ultimately destroy the Earth and ourselves with pollution.
The only hope is that stagnant economic growth, reduced consumption, recycling, and forced people to have fewer children would achieve social stability at a level of poverty significantly lower than what we have now.
This viewpoint still resonates today, despite its many inaccuracies.
For instance, the author of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that the world would exhaust its supplies of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
However, even though prices of goods have recently bounced back, they have overall fallen to one-third of the level they were 150 years ago.
Technological innovations replaced mercury in batteries, dental fillings, and thermometers, with mercury consumption dropping by 98% by 2000 and prices falling by 90%.
In broader terms, copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc supplies have exceeded demand since 1946, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new refining technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to be depleted in 1990 and 1992 respectively; today, the reserves of both are higher than those of 1970, despite our consumption having greatly increased.
In the past six years, shale gas has doubled the potential natural gas reserves in the United States and cut the price in half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase by 14 times this century, with developing countries increasing by 24 times.
The Limit of Growth was wrong because the author ignored the greatest resource: our own wisdom.
Population growth began to slow down since the 1960s.
Food supply has not collapsed (15 billion hectares of arable land are being used, in addition to 27 billion hectares of reserves).
Malnutrition rates have already been eradicated by more than half, down from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution didn't faze us.
The Roman club imagines a pastoral past where we had no particulate air pollution, we were all happy farmers, and in the future, the warmth of the chimney would make it hard for us to breathe. Reality is completely the opposite.
In 1900, the world's population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people - roughly one out of every 500 - died from air pollution, with most of it being indoor air pollution.
At present, this ratio has fallen to one death per 2,000 people.
Although the number of deaths from pollution is still higher than that from malaria, its mortality rate is decreasing rather than increasing.
Despite this, the ideas cultivated by "The Limits of Growth" still influence the thinking of the public and elites.
Let's take recycling for example, it's usually just a gesture to make people feel better, but it costs the environment a great deal with little effect.
For example, paper is often sourced from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The programs and government subsidies related to paper recycling bring low-quality paper, which protects resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, concerns about overpopulation have led to policies of self-destruction, such as China's one-child policy and India's forced sterilization.
In addition, despite pesticides and other pollutants being thought to kill off half of humanity, good pesticide regulation has resulted in only 20 annual deaths in the U.S., and the use of pesticides has created a more affordable and abundant food supply.
In reality, relying solely on organic farming – the movement fueled by the pesticide scare – will bring an extra $1 trillion per year in costs to the United States.
Agricultural efficiency will decrease by 16%, and to maintain the current output, another 65 million hectares of farmland, equivalent to half of modern California, would be needed.
Price increases will lead to a decrease in consumption of fruits and vegetables, resulting in severe negative health effects (including an annual increase of tens of thousands of cancer-related deaths).
Obsessing over dark scenarios prevents us from paying attention to the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the greatest killers, and easily treatable diseases still cause 15 million deaths each year, equivalent to a quarter of the total number of deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
When people get out of poverty, most can afford the cost of preventing infectious diseases.
Over the past thirty years, China has lifted 680 million people out of poverty, reducing the global poor population by nearly one billion.
It has brought about a significant improvement in health, lifespan, and living standards.
Forty years of history since the publication of "The Limits to Growth" have shown that we need more, not less, growth.
Trade expansion is estimated to bring in excess of $10 trillion annually by the end of the century, far exceeding the benefits of the timid "good behavior" policy induced by the advocacy of fear.
But this requires abandoning the thinking of anti-growth, and creating a brighter future with our infinite potential.
